> [!Question]
> I hear we talk about enforce json smode, I hear json response format... but I didn't hear us talking about json response schema, why is that?

Because those are three different levels of strictness:

- `json_mode`: “return valid JSON”
- `json response format`: usually “return a JSON object, not free text”
- `json response schema`: “return JSON matching this exact shape”

What we’ve discussed so far is the first two, mostly because the current M2 design is still provider-agnostic and the hard contract already lives on the Python side in [`compile_result.schema.json`](/home/ftu/Droidoes/Obsidian-KDB/kdb_compiler/schemas/compile_result.schema.json) plus [`validate_compile_result.py`](/home/ftu/Droidoes/Obsidian-KDB/kdb_compiler/validate_compile_result.py). In other words, the system already assumes “models are messy, Python is the gate.”

Why schema-constrained generation has not been the lead topic:
- The current wrapper in [`call_model.py`](/home/ftu/Droidoes/Obsidian-KDB/kdb_compiler/call_model.py) does not expose a cross-provider “here is the exact JSON Schema” path.
- Anthropic is the proposed default, and the current implementation does not enforce schema there the way some APIs can.
- We already planned a `response_normalizer.py` layer precisely because we expect fenced JSON, leading prose, and other mild drift.
- A provider-specific schema feature would tighten outputs, but it also couples M2 v1 more strongly to one API surface.

So the short answer is: we did not ignore JSON Schema; we moved the authoritative schema enforcement to post-generation validation instead of generation-time enforcement. That is simpler and more portable for v1.

If you want the strongest possible contract later, the order is:
1. Keep Python-side schema validation no matter what.
2. Add provider-side schema-constrained output where supported.
3. Retain the normalizer as a fallback, because provider guarantees are never perfect across vendors.

> [!Question]
> I still have trouble to understand the rationale for not having a json schema upfront when calling the models... for all words and sentences you had above, there was zero explanation why we don't plan to have schema up front... I can tell you ten reasons why we should but you have not told me one reason why we should not

The real answer is not “schema upfront is bad.” It’s “for this M2 v1, the costs may outweigh the benefits unless we narrow the design.”

The concrete reasons not to require schema-constrained output up front are:

1. Provider portability.
The current plan wants one compiler path across Anthropic, OpenAI, Gemini, and Ollama via [`call_model.py`](/home/ftu/Droidoes/Obsidian-KDB/kdb_compiler/call_model.py). Exact JSON Schema enforcement is not exposed uniformly across those providers, and the current wrapper does not implement it. If we require schema upfront, we either add provider-specific branches now or silently lose the “same compiler path” goal.

2. Anthropic is the default.
Your proposed default is Anthropic Opus 4.7, but the current Anthropic path in [`call_model.py`](/home/ftu/Droidoes/Obsidian-KDB/kdb_compiler/call_model.py) does not enforce a response schema. So “schema upfront” is not just a design preference here; it implies extra implementation work and likely a provider-specific contract.

3. The model should not emit the whole `compile_result` shape anyway.
Parts of [`compile_result.schema.json`](/home/ftu/Droidoes/Obsidian-KDB/kdb_compiler/schemas/compile_result.schema.json) are Python-owned or run-level aggregate fields:
`run_id`, `success`, top-level `errors`, top-level `warnings`.
The model really emits a per-source fragment, not the full artifact. So if we do schema upfront, we should first split out a separate “compiled source response schema” rather than reuse the full artifact schema.

4. It increases the change surface right when prompt/spec iteration is still unstable.
M2 v1 is the first real compile. We are still learning what prompt shape, context shape, and page-intent shape actually work. Hard provider-side schemas are valuable once the contract is stable; before that, they make every prompt/output tweak more expensive.

5. It can create false confidence.
Provider-side schema enforcement only proves “the JSON matches a shape.” It does not prove:
- slugs are sensible
- `outgoing_links` match the body
- page content is semantically correct
- source support is well chosen
We still need Python validation and semantic checks. So schema upfront helps, but it does not replace the hard parts.

So the honest rationale is:
- not because schema upfront is a bad idea
- because in this repo, right now, it pushes us toward provider-specific code, extra wrapper work, and a schema split we have not designed yet

If you want my actual engineering recommendation after your pushback: for a single-provider M2 v1, I would lean toward adding schema-constrained output for the per-source model response. I would not use the full `compile_result` schema directly; I would define a smaller response schema for one compiled source plus log entries, keep Python aggregation, and still keep `response_normalizer` and `validate_compile_result` as the safety net. That is the strongest version of the design.

